SELIKOWITZ J:}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
This is an appeal against the decision and order handed down by the Competition Tribunal (hereinafter \'93the Tribunal\'94) on 8 April 2002 following a remittal hearing held in terms of the provisions of Part D of chapter 5 of the Competitions Act, No. 89 of 1998 (hereinafter \'93the Act\'94).}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Appellant is Patensie Sitrus Beherend Beperk, a public company duly registered and incorporated during 1999 in accordance with the company laws of the Republic of South Africa.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
First Respondent is the Competition Commission of South Africa, (hereinafter \'93the Commission\'94) a juristic person established in terms of section 19 of the Act}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Second Respondent is Jacobus Johannes Petrus Bezuidenhout, a citrus farmer and the owner of the farm \'93Fairview\'94 situated in the Gamtoos River Valley (hereinafter \'93the GRV\'94) in the Eastern Cape. At }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
all material times Second Respondent was a shareholder in Appellant.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Third Respondent is Jan Daniel Du Preez, a citrus farmer who owns the farm \'93Hardleigh\'94 in the Gamtoos River Valley. Third Respondent was also a shareholder in Appellant.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
The hearing before the Competition Tribunal concerned a consolidation of two referrals to the Tribunal. The one referral related to complaints made by the Second and Third Respondents which raised }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
the issue of conduct prohibited by the Act. The complaint was referred by the Honourable Mr Justice Horn from the South Eastern Cape Local Division of the High Court of South Africa in terms of }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
section 65 2 (b) of the Act. The other referral was by the Commission in terms of section 50 of the Act pursuant to a complaint. }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
It is unnecessary to set out the rather complex history of the disputes which }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
en route}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
 to the remittal hearing before the Tribunal first came before the High Court both in the Eastern Cape and in Gauteng and also before the Tribunal for interim relief. Suffice to say that at a pre  }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
hearing conference the parties agreed to consolidate the two referrals before the Tribunal. }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Background to and History of Appellant }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
The history of the citrus industry in South Africa as also the genesis of Appellant were concisely described by the Tribunal as follows:}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\rtlch \ltrch
\'93}{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
The South African citrus industry accounts for approximately 2% of the total citrus production in the world market. Approximately 65% of the citrus produced in South Africa is exported, the balance either being sold in local markets or to a local processor to be made into juice.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
In 1939 citrus co-operatives \'96 many of which had been established in the \'91twenties - belonged to the South African Citrus Exchange, a central co-operative which handled more than 81% of the fruit produced in South Africa.\~  At about this time, the government established a statutory control board which brought the single channel marketing system into being.\~  In terms of this system, all packers (co-operative and independent) had to channel the packed fruit to the co-operative Citrus Exchange, later replaced by Outspan International.\~  Prior to the repeal, in 1996, of the Marketing Act of 1968, the citrus industry had deregulated the selling of fruit on the South African market.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
[Appellant is the successor of an entity] originally registered as Patensie Citrus Co-operative Limited in terms of the Co-operative Societies Act 29 of 1939.\~  Until July 1998 it conducted its packing and distribution operations as a co-operative under}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
the Co-operative Societies\'92 Act.\~  On 3rd\~ July 1998 the co-operative was converted into a limited liability company.\~  All former members of the co-operative became shareholders in (or \'91members\'92 of) a restructured company, Patensie Sitrus Beperk (\'91PSB\'92).\~  The company\'92s Articles of Association purported to eliminate any distinction between producers and members.\~  However a producer was a specific type of member because certain members were not producers, but only made use of the trading department which supplied farm equipment.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
In March 1999, a second company, namely Patensie Sitrus Beherend Beperk, the [Appellant] in the present matter, was incorporated. The directors of PSB became the directors of, and sole shareholders in, the respondent.\~  In September 1999 a special resolution was passed bringing the respondent\'92s Articles into line with those of PSB.\~  Members of PSB, including [Second and Third Respondents], exchanged their shares in PSB for shares in the [Appellant].\~  It appears that most of these transfers were affected in late 1999.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
The respondent is a public company. It is the holding company of, and the majority shareholder in, PSB.\~  It is envisaged that, once the restructuring process is complete, Patensie will be the sole shareholder in PSB.\~  The respondent\'92s shareholders are all citrus farmers.\~  It provides packing and marketing facilities through its subsidiary, PSB, which it refers to as its operational arm.\'94}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Appellant\'92s Articles of Association}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Appellant submits that, in contrast with other companies, it does not operate as \'91an ordinary company or independently from its members\'92. It contends that its Articles reflect the long path that has been trodden. The Articles prescribe specific rights and obligations relating to }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
inter alia }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
membership; the servicing of the Appellant\'92s long-term loans; the transfer of its shares; the termination of membership, and the utilisation of its packing and marketing services.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
The origin of these provisions is to be found by reference to the provisions which existed under the old co-operative and which were relocated in Appellant\'92s }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Articles of Association.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Under the co-operative members held pack rights (\'93}{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
pakregte}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
\'94) which entitled them to an annual quota fruit which could be packed at the co-operative\'92s pack shed. The individual pack rights were determined through a complex formula based on the individual members\'92 financial contribution to redeeming the packing facilities capital liability in relation to the total available packing capacity of the pack house and not the volume of fruit actually delivered.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
The pack rights were used to calculate the \'93}{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
pack right levy}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
\'94 (\'93}{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
pakregheffing}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
\'94) which was the capital contribution that members were liable to pay to the co-operative on resignation. This capital contribution represented the }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
pro rata}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
 obligation of each member for the long-term debt of the co-operative. This system was carried over from the co-operative to PSB, the predecessor of the Appellant. }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
With the conversion from PSB to Appellant, a revised system for the calculation of the shareholders\'92 capital levies was introduced after consultation with the members. Henceforth the levies would be determined by the number of crates of fruit delivered across the Appellant\'92s weighbridge by each of the members. It appears that the size of a member\'92s shareholding in Appellant is approximately proportionate such member\'92s output. The size of a member\'92s shareholding correlates with the capacity of the resources of the pack house used by that shareholder. Accordingly, the capital levy refers to a member\'92s }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
pro rata}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
share of the capital obligation incurred by the company in investing in infrastructure and equipment. The capital levy (member\'92s }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
pro rata}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
 share of the debt) is directly proportional to the current shareholding of that member. Thus, if a member holds one }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
per cent}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
 of the issued shares in Appellant, such member is liable for one }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
per cent}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
 of the gross debt of the company.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
The packing cost payable by each farmer using Appellant\'92s facilities is calculated by reference to the quantity and the quality of fruit delivered by that particular member.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Otherwise, members\'92 rights remained the same as they had been under both the former co-operative and under PSB.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
In Appellant\'92s answering affidavit, its secretary Mr Jacobus Stephan Du Toit states: }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\rtlch \ltrch
\'93}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
I have already mentioned hereinbefore that the Respondent\'92s Articles of Association are the standard ones found in Schedule 1, Table A of the Companies Act 61 of 1973, with certain additions thereto }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
in a document termed \'91}{\i\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Toevoeging tot Statuut van Patensie Sitrus Beherend Beperk om Voorsiening te Maak vir Speciale Kontraktuele Voorwaardes Tussen Lede en die Maatskappy\'92}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 }{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
to }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
cater for the }{\i\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
sui generis}{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
 nature of the Respondent and the purposes for which it was established.\'94}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs23\lang2057
It is the addendum, which forms part of the Articles which contains the provisions that were the subject of the enquiry undertaken by the Tribunal and are - save in respect of Article 110 which the Tribunal declined to strike down - the provisions relevant in this }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs23\lang2057
appeal.}
