\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
The Process: From Citrus Farm to Consumer}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
It is useful to consider the processes followed from the point where the citrus fruit is produced on the producers farm until it reaches the shelves of retail outlets. The explanation will also note Appellant\'92s practices. }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Production Stage:}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
The farmers grow the fruit on their farms utilising various resources including the land, labour, equipment, water, fertilisers and pesticides. When harvested the fruit has to go through further preparatory and handling processes before it is marketable for consumption. }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Market Preparation:}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
The citrus fruit is washed, disinfected and sometimes waxed. It is graded for quality and size before being packed in suitable containers. These containers are palletised and the fruit is inspected to ensure }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
compliance with official regulations. These functions are normally performed in a specially equipped packhouse. Farmers who do not have their own packhouses will normally deliver the fruit to a }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
packhouse for processing as aforesaid. In Appellant\'92s case it has a modern packhouse. Its facilities were updated and improved some four years ago at a cost of R21 million. There are in excess of two }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
hundred packhouses in South Africa and Appellant packs and arranges to market approximately five per cent of the country\'92s total citrus production. Appellant packs and arranges to market }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
approximately seventy per cent of the citrus fruit produced in the Gamtoos River Valley. Farmers do not sell their fruit to Appellant - neither money nor risk passes when the fruit is delivered to Appellant\'92s }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
packhouse.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Transportation to point of intake}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
:}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
After preparation and packaging, the fruit is transported to the next \'93}{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
station}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
\'94. Where the fruit is not destined for export, the \'93}{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
station}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
\'94 could be a municipal market, a local wholesaler or retailer or a processing facility which might process extract the juice or manufacture a citrus preserve or similar product. Some sixty five per cent of the citrus fruit produced in South Africa is marketed overseas. Where the fruit is exported, the next \'93}{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
station}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
\'94 is a seaport or an airport. The fruit which travels by road or rail is received at the port by a marketing agent. Appellant appoints a number of marketing agents on a per season basis to attend to the citrus fruit which it markets on behalf of its members. }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
The fruit is not sold to the marketing agent and the producer continues to carry the risk.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Port Handling:}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
The citrus fruit is inspected and then placed into cold storage to bring the temperature down to required standards for shipment. The fruit is then loaded into a ship or aeroplane.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Shipping:}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
The fruit is shipped - less frequently, flown - to its overseas destination.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Overseas Port of Entry;}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
On arrival at the destination port the fruit is cleared for entry, stored and then forwarded by clearing agents to the wholesale markets, interim service providers or customers who can be fruit importers or }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
retail suppliers. It is only at this point that the citrus fruit is sold and where the price which the producer will receive is determined. Until this point of sale the producer continues to carry the risk. Even at }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
this point of sale the risk includes a need to destroy fruit that has deteriorated or fails to comply with local regulations.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
End consumer:}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
The fruit is thereafter sold to the retailer and, in turn to the consumer.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Price received by the producers }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
South African citrus fruit farmers have no influence upon the market and the price received for their fruit. They are \'93price takers\'94 on the international market. Because of the fact that the overwhelming }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
majority of the citrus fruit handled by Appellant in the Gamtoos River Valley is destined for export and because that market accounts for approximately ninety three per cent of the income of Appellant\'92s }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
members, the parties before the Tribunal focussed almost exclusively on the export market. Nothing turns on the ommission to analyse the local citrus market. The determinations made in respect of the }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
export market apply with equal force to the local marketing of citrus fruit. Certain costs are deducted from the market price received before the producer receives payment for his citrus crop. Those }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
include the following costs directly related to the packing and marketing process.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Production costs:}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
These are the costs of preparing the fruit for the market.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
DIP costs:}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
These include transport costs and statutory levies which are incurred when the fruit reaches the point of intake.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
FOB costs}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
:}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
The costs of shipping, handling, storage, loading and insurance from the point of intake until the fruit is loaded into the ship or aeroplane.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Sea or air freight}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
:}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
These costs are significant as they are US dollar related and a fluctuating exchange rate can have an effect.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Import duty:}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Also a significant cost, it can vary from market to market and over time.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Overseas costs:}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
The cost of clearing, storage in cooling facilities and transport to the point of sale.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Appellant\'92s heads of argument filed before this court, it is stated that:}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\rtlch \ltrch
\'93}{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
The essence of the Appellant\'92s case is that, with reference to its co-operative origins and background; its peculiar relationship with its members, who are all citrus producers, and\~  the exigencies and demands of the highly competitive citrus market in which it operates, the Articles of Association had been formulated and agreed to in precisely the disputed form in order to enable its members to compete effectively in that market, to the benefit of all its members, the end-consumer and the national economy.\~  It was argued that, in the light of the proven facts, the Articles of Association of the Appellant constitute no more and no less than an ordinary contractual arrangement which does not fall foul of the Act and which should not have enjoyed the attention of the Commission in the first place.\'94}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
It is also submitted that:}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\rtlch \ltrch
\'93}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Since 1928 to the present day, and even after the former co-op had changed into a company, the relationship between the entity itself (currently the Appellant) and its members has not changed: for pro-competitive, sound economic, cost-effective and efficiency reasons, a number of farmers have come together to pool their resources for the purposes of packing and marketing, thereby ultimately ensuring a higher net return to themselves\'94 }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
and further that: }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\rtlch \ltrch
\'93}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
The whole purpose of the joint packing and marketing arrangement is to manage the packing and marketing facilities on a more economical basis. }{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
The second paragraph of the pre-amble to the }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Additions to the Appellant's Articles of Association makes special reference to the pro-competitive gains expected to flow from the said arrangement.\'94 }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
A considerable amount of evidence was advanced to establish that the joint packing and marketing of citrus fruit by a number of farmers was beneficial. That it benefits the producers who utilise the }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
services would appear to be clear. What is in issue, however, is whether the means chosen by Appellant and its members to achieve their stated goals contravenes the Act. More particularly, whether the }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\fs24\lang2057
\'93}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
arrangement\'94 between Appellant and its members who are the producers amounts, in the circumstances, to an unjustified abuse of dominance as is prohibited by section 8 of the Act. It is useful at this }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
stage to set out out a number of matters which bear upon the decision in this matter. Firstly, Appellant is no longer a co-operative. Since March 1999 Appellant is a public company. It remains, however, }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
possible to view the company as the vehicle through which its shareholders jointly undertake the packing and marketing of their citrus produce. So viewed, Appellant is a public company which exhibits }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
many of the characteristics of an agricultural co-operative.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Secondly, a co-operative is an enterprise linking assets, business activities, financial obligations and people in a distinctive way. Care must constantly be taken to recognise and in some cases to distinguish the dual status of people who are both its customers and the owners of the co-operative, }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
in casu}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
, the members to whom earnings will be distributed according to customer patronage. }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Thirdly, large agricultural co-operatives are very different from what they were a century, or even half a century ago. South African citrus farmers have seen major changes in the citrus industry and, in particular, in the packing, processing and marketing of citrus fruit. The industry has undergone important institutional changes over the past eight decades. As noted the legal form of the entity undertaking the packing and marketing of citrus fruit in the Gamtoos River Valley has changed from that of a co-operative (of which the farmers were members) to that of a limited liability company of which the farmers are now shareholders. A further important change concerns the marketing of the crop. The international marketing of agricultural produce was, until recently, the exclusive preserve of a number of statutory \'91control boards\'92 established in terms of The Marketing Act No. 59 of 1968. This statute was repealed by the Marketing of Agricultural Products Act, No. 47 of 1996. The upshot is that the packing companies and others who desire to offer fruit on the international market will market the fruit through the agency of one of the many market agents who undertake the marketing function.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
The advantages gained by farmers and producers of food forming co-operatives has long been recognised in foreign jurisdictions. The special treatment usually affords limited exemption from the reach of competition law. Wherever such special treatment has been given it is to be found in statutory enactments. In the United States since 1914, section 6 of the }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Clayton Act}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
 (36 Stat. 730 [1914]) partially exempted agricultural organisations from the competition laws. The }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Capper-Volstead Act }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
(42 Stat. 388 [1922]) extended the exemption to capital stock agricultural co-operatives.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Articles 32 to 38 of the }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
European Community Treaty}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
 establish a special regime for agriculture and allow the Council to limit the application of the rules of competition law in regards to the production }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
and trade in agricultural products.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Indeed, the fact that the Act does not exempt agricultural activities from its reach ought to sound a note of caution in the approach to the issues raised in this matter. It should be noted that the Act does }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
allow for agreements and practices to be granted exemption from the provisions of Chapter 2 which deals with prohibited practices including abuse of dominance. (Section 10). }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
In seeking to determine}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
the relevant market, the analysis advanced by Warren CJ in the United States Supreme Court in }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Brown Shoe v United States}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
, 370 U.S. 294 (1962) at 325 provides a useful analysis and insight into the }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
appropriate methodology.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\rtlch \ltrch
\'93}{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
The outer boundaries of a product market are determined by the reasonable interchangeability of use or the cross-elasticity of demand between the product itself and substitutes for it. }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
However, within this broad market, well-defined submarkets may exist which, in themselves, constitute product markets for antitrust purposes. The boundaries of such a submarket}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
may be determined by examining such practical indicia as industry or public recognition of the submarket as a separate economic entity, the product's peculiar characteristics and uses, }
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
unique production facilities, distinct customers, distinct prices, sensitivity to price changes, and specialized vendors.\'94}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
And, at 336-337:}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
"The criteria to be used in determining the appropriate geographic market are essentially similar to those used to determine the relevant product market. . . .}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Moreover, just as a product submarket may have significance as the proper "line of commerce," so may a geographic submarket be considered the appropriate "section of the country." . . . . Congress prescribed a pragmatic, factual approach to the definition of the relevant market and not a formal, legalistic one. The geographic market selected must, therefore, both "correspond to the commercial realities" of the industry and be economically [370 US 294, 337] significant. Thus, although the geographic market in some instances may encompass the entire Nation, under other circumstances it may be as small as a single metropolitan area.\'94}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
The }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
United Kingdom Office of Fair Trading Market Definition Guideline}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
 also provides useful guidance in the approach to be taken when defining the relevant product market from the demand side which is appropriate here.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-720{\rtlch \ltrch
\'93}{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
3.1 \tab The process usually starts by looking at a relatively narrow potential definition. This would normally be the products which the parties to an agreement both produce or the products which are the subject of a complaint. Common sense will normally indicate the narrowest potential market definition. The Director General then considers how customers would react if prices were raised a small but significant amount above competitive levels.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
3.2\tab Common practice in both Europe and the US is to consider a price 5-10 per cent above competitive levels. This will normally be the Director General\'92s approach, although, in}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-720{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
practice, it is often difficult to quantify a potential price rise. The 5-10 per cent test is a rough guide rather than a rule.\'94}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
The }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
European Commission}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
 notice on }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
The Definition of the Relevant Market for the Purposes of Community Competition Law}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
 (Published in the Official Journal: OJ C 372 on 9/12/1997) after describing market definition as a tool to identify and define the boundaries of competition between firms goes on to record that:}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\rtlch \ltrch
\'93}{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
The objective of defining a market in both its product and geographic dimension is to identify those actual competitors of the undertakings involved that are capable of constraining their behaviour and of preventing them from behaving independently of an effective competitive pressure. It is from this perspective, that the market definition makes it possible, inter alia, to calculate market shares that would convey meaningful information regarding market power for the purposes of assessing dominance or for the purposes of applying Article 85.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
It follows from the above, that the concept of relevant market is different from other concepts of market often used in other contexts. For instance, companies often use the term market to refer to the area where it sells its products or to refer broadly to the industry or sector where it belongs.\'94}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
This last observation finds resonance - albeit by way of a failure to recognise the distinction - in Appellant\'92s submissions as to the appropriate product market definition.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
In their text }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Economics Of E.C. Competition Law Concepts, Application And Measurement}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
 (1999) at p.49), S Bishop and W Walker state that:}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\qj{\rtlch \ltrch
\'93}{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
The relevant market contains all those substitute products and regions which provide a significant competitive constraint on the products and regions of interest . The relevant market can be defined as a collection of products such that a (hypothetical) single supplier of that collection would be able to increase price profitably. Defining the relevant market in this way ensures that all products which pose a significant competitive constraint on the parties under investigation are taken into consideration. In this section, the application of these principles in practice is discussed and the following guiding principle proposed: a relevant market is something worth monopolising. A market is worth monopolising if monopolisation permits prices to be profitably increased. This will be the case if the collection of products contained in this "market" are not subject to significant competitive constraints by products outside the market.\'94}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
For the assessment of demand substitution the so-called "5% test" or "SSNIP test" (SSNIP is the popular acronym for "}{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
small but significant non-transitory increase in price}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
") is useful. This test which was first used by the }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
United States Federal Trade Commission}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
 and is now the test proposed in paragraph 14 of the }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
European Commission}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
 Notice referred to above. The SSNIP test is increasingly being made use of by competition authorities throughout the world.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Application Of the legal and economic principles to the facts}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
It is, in my view, apparent from the evidence that the undertaking of packing and arranging for the marketing of citrus fruit is a service offered and rendered by Appellant to citrus producers. It is trite that a product market can include goods or services of this kind.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Although notionally the market for the sale of citrus on international markets can be described as a \'93}{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
market}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
\'94 it is not the market that is at all relevant for purposes of the present enquiry. Common sense dictates that the \'93}{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
narrowest potential market definition\'94}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
 in this instance is not the sale of citrus on some distant international market but the rendering of the services in question within the GRV. It is in this market that the services which are the \'93}{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
subject of the complaint\'94}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
 are rendered. The evidence is that there are other parties engaged in offering the relevant services in the GRV.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
The fact that Appellant would have itself viewed for present purposes as the sum of its members and that it does not perceive itself as competing with like services offered and undertaken by other fruit packers in the region is not a determinative factor for purposes of defining the parameters of the relevant market.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
In defining the relevant market Appellant and its expert witnesses have failed to have regard to the }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
hypothetical monopolist}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
 undertaking the relevant services. They advance a business model that is constrained by and reliant upon the characteristics peculiar to Appellant, including the anti-competitive structures and practices that are the very subject matter of the complaint.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
In its grounds of appeal, Appellant asserts, in relation to the Tribunal\'92s finding that the relevant product market is the market for packing and marketing service in the GRV, that: \'93}{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
On all the evidence the Tribunal should have found that, by their own volition and choice, the members/shareholders of the Appellant are not competing in the notional "packing and marketing services market", whether in the Gamtoos River Valley or anywhere else\'94}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
As noted, it is not competition engaged in by Appellant\'92s members that is in issue. In issue, is competition by Appellant itself in the market in which it is engaged.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
In any event, a voluntary withdrawal from competition whether contractually confirmed or not is not a decisive factor in defining the relevant market. }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Per contra}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
, it is irrelevant. Significantly, the ground of appeal acknowledges a \'93notional\'94 packing and marketing services market in which Appellant submits that its members do not compete.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Appellant also emphasised that it did not seek to profit from its services to its members and that the amount deducted by Appellant from the selling price of the fruit was limited to Appellant\'92s costs including the cost of servicing its capital loan debts.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Be that as it may, the producers are required to compensate Appellant for the services they utilise. The fact that the amount is limited to Appellant\'92s costs does not make it any less a }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
quid pro quo}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
. In fact, Appellant\'92s costs as deducted may exceed the charges - including a profit margin - at other packhouses which offer equivalent services.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
A region the size of the GRV can comprise a relevant market. The valley is approximately some one hundred kilometres long and there are approximately one hundred and ten citrus farmers in the GRV.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}
\par \pard\plain \s21\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult1\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
In regard to the actual current position, Appellant\'92s affidavits demonstrate that the establishment of pack-houses is extremely capital intensive and beyond the reach of most citrus producers in the GRV. Appellant spent R21 million on its packhouse some four years ago. Furthermore, although there are other packing facilities in the GRV and the neighbouring Sundays River Valley \'93}{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
there is no, or very little flow of packing services between these areas}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
